	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/37549009172?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Background. Education is one of the key elements in the promotion of a thorough paradigm for active aging. The aim of this study is to analyze factors that contribute the empowerment of older adults in a rural Mexican community and, thus, promote active aging. Methods. The study was conducted in a rural Mexican community (Valle del Mezquital), based on an action-research paradigm. One hundred and fifty-five elderly subjects with elementary school education participated in a formal training program promoting gerontological development and health education. Participants in turn became coordinators of mutual-help groups (gerontological nucleus) in Mexico. In-depth interviews were carried out to assess the empowerment after training for active aging. Results. It was found that there was an increasing feeling of empowerment, creativity and self-fulfillment among participants. Among the main factors that positively influenced training of the elderly toward active aging were the teaching of gerontology topics themselves; besides, their motivation, the self-esteem, the increased undertaking of responsibility, the feeling of belonging to the group, and the sharing of information based on personal experience and on gerontological knowledge. Conclusion. The main factors that contribute to empowerment of older adults in a rural Mexican community for participate in active aging programs are the training and teaching of gerontology topics themselves; besides, their interest, experience and involvement. © 2007 de la Luz Martinez-Maldonado et al.; licensee BioMed Central Ltd.},
	keywords = {Activities of Daily Living; Aged; Aging; Female; Health Education; Health Knowledge, Attitudes, Practice; Health Promotion; Health Services for the Aged; Humans; Male; Mexico; Middle Aged; Power (Psychology); Program Development; Qualitative Research; Rural Health; Rural Health Services; Self Care; Self Concept; Social Support; academic achievement; adult; aged; aging; article; community; creativity; empowerment; female; gerontological research; gerontology; health education; health promotion; human; major clinical study; male; Mexico; motivation; personal experience; qualitative analysis; responsibility; rural area; self actualization; self esteem; training; attitude to health; behavior; daily life activity; elderly care; health; health education; health promotion; methodology; middle aged; organization and management; program development; psychological aspect; qualitative research; rural health care; self care; self concept; social support},
